<h1>@KJ{{oneself^part}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @KJ{{oneself^part}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@KJ{{oneself^part}} can be a reflexive pronoun that refers back to a human subject, which is then contrasted with someone else.
Of the two usages of @KJ{{oneself^part}}, this one is the correct one if any of the following is true:
<ol>
<li> the referent is an agent
<li> the subject is generic
<li> @KJ{{oneself^part}} cannot be replaced by an implicit or explicit 3rd person pronoun.
</ol>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^book^person}}ha@KJ{{oneself^part}}no@KJ{{country}}no@KJ{{sentence^change}}wo@KT{{yuni-ku}}
      dato@KJ{{think}}tteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The Japanese think that their country's culture is unique.
  </td> </tr>
</table>

</p>

<p>
If @KJ{{oneself^part}} does not satisy the conditions above then it is not a contrastive marker and is instead referring back
to a human subject with whom the speaker empathises.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{soil^rice*field}}ha@KJ{{happiness^child}}ga@KJ{{oneself^part}}wo@KJ{{love}}shiteirukotowo@KJ{{know}}rimasendeshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Tsuchida didn't know that Sachiko loved him.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

